0xa99f0.str_content:
oemhp_loadSSHKey    : Used to authorize a SSH Key File from an URL.
Example : oemhp_loadSSHKey /map1/config1/ -source http://user:pwd@192.168.1.1/SSHkey1.pub
          oemhp_loadSSHKey /map1/accounts1/<lname> -source http://user:pwd@192.168.1.1/SSHkey1.pub
          where <lname> is the name of the user that an SSH key is to be loaded.
          The SSHkeyhash of a given user is located in the directory /map1/accounts/<lname>.
 Usage: protocol://username:password@hostname:port/filename
  The protocol field is mandatory and must be either HTTP or HTTPS.
  The username:password field is optional.
  The hostname field is mandatory.
  The port field is optional.
  The filename field is mandatory.

0xa9cbc.name: a_POWER_The_power_command_is_used_to_change_the_powe
0xa9cbc.str_content:
POWER  : The power command is used to change the power state of the server
 and is limited to users with the Power and Reset privilege
Usage:
  power          -- Displays the current server power state
  power on       -- Turns the server on
  power off      -- Turns the server off
  power off hard -- Force the server off using press and hold
  power reset    -- Reset the server

0xa9f04.name: a_ONETIMEBOOT_View_or_alter_the_server_One_Time_Boot

ONETIMEBOOT: View or alter the server One-Time Boot setting.
The supported settings are a subset of settings found in other interfaces.
Usage:
  onetimeboot                -- Display the current state.
  onetimeboot usb            -- Set to USB.
  onetimeboot ip             -- Set to Intelligent Provisioning.
  onetimeboot smartstartLX   -- Set to IP Smart Start Linux PE.
  onetimeboot netdev1        -- Set to Network Device 1.
  onetimeboot none           -- Disable One-Time Boot.

0xaa0f8.name: a_VM_Virtual_media_commands_Usage_vm_device_insert_p
0xaa0f8.str_content:
VM     : Virtual media commands.
Usage:
  vm <device> insert <path> -- Inserts an image
CLP COMMAND: set /map1/oemhp_vm1/<device> oemhp_image=<path>
  vm <device> eject -- Ejects an image
CLP COMMAND: set /map1/oemhp_vm1/<device> oemhp_image=none
  vm device get -- Gets the status of the virtual media
CLP COMMAND: show /map1/oemhp_vm1/<device>
  vm <device> set <options> -- Sets the status of the virtual media
CLP COMMAND: set /map1/oemhp_vm1/<device> <property=value>
Command Options:
  Device is floppy or cdrom
  CLP device is floppydr or cddr
  Path is the url to the media image
  Access option is write_protect or write_allow
   (cannot be set for CD devices)
  Boot options are connect, disconnect, as well as
   boot_always, boot_once, or no_boot (these 3 cannot be set for
   floppy devices on UEFI-capable systems)
  CLP properties are oemhp_connect, oemhp_boot, oemhp_wp

0xab350.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_the_power_cap_setting_for_th
0xab350.str_content:
Displays and modifies the power cap setting for the server. A power cap
wattage of zero indicates that power capping is disabled.
Examples:
    show /system1/oemhp_power1 oemhp_pwrcap - displays the current power capping level
    set /system1/oemhp_power1  oemhp_pwrcap=<n> where n is an integer cap value in watts
       <n> must be greater than or equal to oemhp_serverminpower
       <n> must be less than or equal to oemhp_powersupplycapacity
    set /system1/oemhp_power1  oemhp_pwrcap=0 - setting power cap to zero disables power capping

0xab57c.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_the_power_mode_setting_for_t
0xab57c.str_content:
Displays and modifies the power mode setting for the server.
Modes:  
  0 - No Capping  
  1 - Max Performance with Redundancy  
  2 - Max Redundancy  
  3 - User Selectable Advanced Power Capping  
       Note - For mode 3 a capping value for the enclosure must be provided using set oemhp_pwrcap  
Examples: show /system1/oemhp_power1  oemhp_pwrmode   
          set /system1/oemhp_power1  oemhp_pwrmode=<n> where n is an integer value from 0-3

0xab748.name: a_PRODABR_samples_the_power_meter_every_five_minutes
0xab748.str_content:
#PRODABR samples the power meter every five minutes and records both the average   
 power and the peak power consumed since the last sample was obtained.   
   
 oemhp_PresentPower        - Displays the average power reading from the last sample.  
 oemhp_AvgPower            - Displays the average power reading from the past 24 hours.  
 oemhp_MaxPower            - Displays the greatest peak power reading from the past 24 hours.  
 oemhp_MinPower            - Displays the minimum average power reading from the past 24 hours.  
 oemhp_powersupplycapacity - Displays the power supply's total capacity in watts.  
 oemhp_servermaxpower      - Displays the server's maximum power capacity in watts.  
 oemhp_serverminpower      - Displays the server's minimum power capacity in watts.

0xaba68.name: a_PRODABR_samples_the_power_meter_every_five_minutes
0xaba68.str_content:
#PRODABR samples the power meter every five minutes and records both the average   
 power and the peak power consumed since the last sample was obtained. Peak power  
 is specific to SL servers which do not have power capping.  
   
 oemhp_peakmeasuredpower   - Displays the peak measured power reading.

0xabba0.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_the_warning_type_Valid_value
0xabba0.str_content:
Displays and modifies the warning type.
     Valid values are :
     1 - Disable warnings
     2 or average - Warnings based on average power consumption
     3 or peak    - Warnings based on peak power consumption
Examples: show /system1/oemhp_power1 warning_type   
          set /system1/oemhp_power1  warning_type=<n> where n is one of the above options

0xabd10.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_the_warning_threshold_for_po
0xabd10.str_content:
Displays and modifies the warning threshold for power consumption.
Examples: show /system1/oemhp_power1 warning_threshold  
          set /system1/oemhp_power1 warning_threshold=<n> where n is the threshold in watts.
The valid range of values for warning_threshold is between oemhp_serverminpower and 
          oemhp_powersupplycapacity.

0xabe6c.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_the_length_of_time_in_minute
0xabe6c.str_content:
Displays and modifies the length of time in minutes that power consumption must remain
above the warning threshold before a SNMP alert is triggered.
Example:   
show /system1/oemhp_power1 warning_duration  
set /system1/oemhp_power1  warning_duration=<n> where n is the time limit in minutes.
The valid range of values for warning_duration is between 1 and 240. If the value provided
is not a multiple of 5, it will be rounded up to the nearest multiple of 5.

0xac044.name: a_Displays_the_firmware_version_number_for_the_power
0xac044.str_content:

0xac0c8.name: a_Displays_and_modifies_Server_Automatic_Power_On_se
0xac0c8.str_content:
Displays and modifies Server Automatic Power On setting. 
Example : show /system1/oemhp_power1 oemhp_auto_pwr 
          set /system1/oemhp_power1 oemhp_auto_pwr=on 
          Valid values are : 
                 ON  - turns on automatic power on with minimum delay 
                 15,30,45,60,random - automatic power on with a timed delay starting when #ILO
                     finishes booting.  Random is a delay up to 120 seconds.

0xad320.name: a_Displays_the_system_boot_configuration_information
0xad320.str_content:
Displays the system boot configuration information.
Example: show /system1/bootconfig1 

Possible boot sources for the system. The values for servers
not supporting booting from the Network:
BootFmCd     : bootsource1
BootFmFloppy : bootsource2
BootFmDrive  : bootsource3
BootFmUSBKey : bootsource4

For systems with booting from the Network: 
BootFmCd     : bootsource1
BootFmFloppy : bootsource2
BootFmDrive  : bootsource3
BootFmUSBKey : bootsource4
BootFmNetwork: bootsource5

On UEFI-capable systems in legacy boot mode, the BootFmFloppy option is
no longer available, so BootFmDrive is now bootsource2, BootFmUSBKey 
is bootsource3, and BootFmNetwork (when applicable) is bootsource4. 

To display the bootorder corresponding to the bootsource, run
show -all /system1/bootconfig1 

For systems that support UEFI, the oemhp_uefibootsourceN targets
are listed in their respective boot order.  Oemhp_description 
provides a description of the UEFI boot option.  Setting bootorder
will rearrange the UEFI boot sources as specified.

0xb29c0.name: a_Displays_or_modifies_PRODABR_virtual_media_floppy_
0xb29c0.str_content:
Displays or modifies #PRODABR virtual media floppy information. This feature
requires an advanced license key.
Examples: 
  show /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 - displays the current properties and values 
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 <property=value> - modifies the property value 
Example showing the steps to connect an floppy image for one-time boot
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_image=http://12.21.34.43/boot.img
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_boot=connect
    <At this point, verify that oemhp_connect=yes and #ILO network settings are configured to access the image>
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_boot=once
    <One can substitute 'once' for 'always' or 'never' as desired>
    <These boot options cannot be set for floppy devices on UEFI-capable systems>
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_wp=yes
    <Optional write protection setting; possible values are 'yes' and 'no'>
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_boot=disconnect
    <This command disconnects the image>

0xb2dbc.name: a_Displays_or_modifies_PRODABR_virtual_media_CD_ROM_

Displays or modifies #PRODABR virtual media CD-ROM information. This feature
requires an advanced license key.
Examples:
  show /map1/oemhp_vm1/cddr1 - displays the current properties and values

  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/cddr1 oemhp_boot=connect
    <At this point, verify that oemhp_connect=yes and #ILO network settings are configured to access the image>
    <To disconnect the image later, run 'set /map1/oemhp_vm1/cddr1 oemhp_boot=disconnect'>
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/cddr1 oemhp_boot=once
    <One can substitute 'once' for 'always' or 'never' as desired>
  set /map1/oemhp_vm1/floppydr1 oemhp_boot=disconnect
    <This command disconnects the image>

 'config' 'admin'
Example: set oemhp_ssoadministrator=login,oemhp_rc

0xb4b84.name: a_oemhp_ssoserver_reflects_the_records_of_HP_SSO_com
0xb4b84.str_content:
oemhp_ssoserver reflects the records of HP SSO-compliant applications registered
 for use with this #ILO.
HP SSO-compliant applications can be registered by name or by certificate.
Use 'create' to add a new HP SSO record using network name.
 example: create hpsim.net
Use 'load' to import the trusted certificate using the network name.
 example: load hpsim.net
Use 'delete' to remove a record by index.
 example: delete 2

0xb5bb0.name: a_load_Used_to_move_a_binary_image_from_an_URL_to_th
0xb5bb0.str_content:
load    : Used to move a binary image from an URL to the MAP or System.
 Usage: protocol://username:password@hostname:port/filename
  The protocol field is mandatory and must be either HTTP or HTTPS.
  The username:password field is optional.
  The hostname field is mandatory.
  The port field is optional.
  The filename field is mandatory.

 The CLP only performs a cursory syntax verification of the <URL>
 value. You must visually ensure the URL is valid. Firmware components
 loaded will be flashed onto the system, replacing the existing versions.
 If the firmware flash was successful, then the status_tag of COMMAND COMPLETED
 will be shown. The management processor is reset if it was updated.

Example : load /map1/firmware1/ -source http://192.168.1.1/images/fw/#ILO4_100.bin

If a Trusted Module is installed and enabled the load
command must include the '-TPM_force' option after the URL. Otherwise the
command will fail.  NOTICE: If a TM is enabled then upgrading without
performing the proper OS encryption procedure will result in loss of access
to your data.  If you do not have your recovery key or have not suspended
encryption software do not flash #ILO.

Example : load /map1/firmware1/ -source http://192.168.1.1/fw/ilo4.bin -TPM_force
